- The hair dryer market is witnessing a shift in consumer preferences towards more advanced and innovative features, driving the segmentation based on product type. Corded and cordless hair dryers offer different levels of convenience and mobility, catering to varying consumer needs. Handheld hair dryers are traditional and versatile options popular among individuals for daily styling needs, while hooded hair dryers are preferred by professionals for more specialized treatments and services.

- The segmentation by price range reflects the diverse consumer base in the hair dryer market. Products priced below US$ 50 target budget-conscious consumers looking for basic functionality, while those in the US$ 50 – US$ 100 range offer a balance between affordability and features, appealing to a wider audience. Hair dryers priced above US$ 100 cater to customers seeking premium quality, advanced technologies, and superior performance, positioning themselves in the high-end segment of the market.

- The segmentation based on application distinguishes between professional and individual users of hair dryers. Professional-grade hair dryers are designed for salon use and styling professionals who require high-performance tools for different hair types and styles. On the other hand, individual consumers choose hair dryers for personal grooming needs, focusing on factors like ease of use, speed, and styling results tailored to their preferences.

- Distribution channels play a crucial role in reaching consumers and influencing purchase decisions in the hair dryer market. Offline channels encompass physical retail stores where customers can interact with products, seek advice from staff, and make informed choices. Online retail channels provide convenience, a wide range of products, and detailed product information, catering to tech-savvy consumers who prefer the ease of online shopping.

